**Node.js** is a JavaScript runtime that lets you run JavaScript outside of a web browser — on servers, command line, or any computer.

```javascript
// Create a simple web server
const http = require('http');

const server = http.createServer((req, res) => {
    res.writeHead(200, { 'Content-Type': 'text/plain' });
    res.end('Hello from Node.js!');
});

server.listen(3000, () => {
    console.log('Server running on port 3000');
});
```

**What Node.js is used for:**
- Backend web servers (APIs, REST, GraphQL)
- Real-time apps (chat, gaming)
- Command-line tools
- Build tools (Webpack, Vite)
- Desktop apps (Electron)

**Key features:**
- Non-blocking, asynchronous
- Uses Chrome's V8 engine
- npm (Node Package Manager) has millions of packages

It's essentially "JavaScript everywhere" — same language on frontend and backend. 🚀
